1. Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE): SLE is a chronic autoimmune disease that can affect multiple organ systems, including the blood, joints, skin, and kidneys. It is characterized by a wide range of symptoms, including autoimmune hemolysis, fever, arthropathy, and delirium.

2. Rheumatoid arthritis (RA): RA is an autoimmune disease that primarily affects the joints. It can also cause systemic symptoms, such as fever and fatigue. Autoimmune hemolysis and delirium are less common symptoms of RA.

3. Scleroderma: Scleroderma is a rare autoimmune disease that affects the skin, blood vessels, and internal organs. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including autoimmune hemolysis, fever, arthropathy, and delirium.

4. Polymyalgia rheumatica (PMR): PMR is an inflammatory condition that causes muscle pain and stiffness. It can also cause systemic symptoms, such as fever and fatigue. Autoimmune hemolysis and delirium are less common symptoms of PMR.

5. Giant cell arteritis (GCA): GCA is an inflammatory condition that affects the blood vessels in the head and neck. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including headache, vision problems, and jaw pain. Autoimmune hemolysis and delirium are less common symptoms of GCA.
6. Antiphospholipid syndrome (APS): APS is an autoimmune disorder that causes blood clots. It can also cause a variety of other symptoms, including autoimmune hemolysis, fever, and delirium.

7. Mixed connective tissue disease (MCTD): MCTD is a rare autoimmune disease that shares features of several other autoimmune diseases, including SLE, RA, and scleroderma. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including autoimmune hemolysis, fever, arthropathy, and delirium.

8. Drug-induced lupus erythematosus (DILE): DILE is a form of lupus that is caused by certain medications. It can cause symptoms that are similar to SLE, including autoimmune hemolysis, fever, arthropathy, and delirium.

9. Infection-related hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (HLH): HLH is a rare condition that can be triggered by infection or other conditions. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including autoimmune hemolysis, fever, and delirium.

10. Hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (HSCT)-associated thrombotic microangiopathy (TMA): TMA is a rare condition that can occur after HSCT. It can cause a variety of symptoms, including autoimmune hemolysis, fever, and delirium.
